# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opc-ua-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The **industrial Internet of things** (**IIoT**) refers to interconnected sensors, instruments, and other devices networked together with computers' industrial applications, including manufacturing and energy management.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] This connectivity allows for data collection, exchange, and analysis, potentially facilitating improvements in productivity and efficiency as well as other economic benefits.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is an evolution of a distributed control system (DCS) that allows for a higher degree of automation by using cloud computing to refine and optimize the process controls.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is enabled by technologies such as cybersecurity, cloud computing, edge computing, mobile technologies, machine-to-machine, 3D printing, advanced robotics, big data, Internet of things, RFID technology, and cognitive computing.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT systems are usually conceived as a layered modular architecture of digital technology.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The device layer refers to the physical components: CPS, sensors or machines.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The network layer consists of physical network buses, cloud computing and communication protocols that aggregate and transport the data to the service layer, which consists of applications that manipulate and combine data into information that can be displayed on the driver dashboard.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The top-most stratum of the stack is the content layer or the user interface.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The history of the IIoT begins with the invention of the programmable logic controller (PLC) by Richard E.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Morley in 1968, which was used by General Motors in their automatic transmission manufacturing division.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] These PLCs allowed for fine control of individual elements in the manufacturing chain.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] In 1975, Honeywell and Yokogawa introduced the world's first DCSs, the TDC 2000 and the CENTUM system, respectively.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] These DCSs were the next step in allowing flexible process control throughout a plant, with the added benefit of backup redundancies by distributing control across the entire system, eliminating a singular point of failure in a central control room.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] As early as in 1994, greater industrial applications were envisioned, as Reza Raji described the concept in IEEE Spectrum as "[moving] small packets of data to a large set of nodes, so as to integrate and automate everything from home appliances to entire factories".
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The concept of the Internet of things first became popular in 1999, through the Auto-ID Center at MIT and related market-analysis publications.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Radio-frequency identification (RFID) was seen by Kevin Ashton (one of the founders of the original Auto-ID Center) as a prerequisite for the Internet of things at that point.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] If all objects and people in daily life were equipped with identifiers, computers could manage and inventory them.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Besides using RFID, the tagging of things may be achieved through such technologies as near field communication, barcodes, QR codes and digital watermarking.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the first consequences of implementing the industrial internet of things (by equipping objects with minuscule identifying devices or machine-readable identifiers) would be to create instant and ceaseless inventory control.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Another benefit of implementing an IIoT system is the ability to create a digital twin of the system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Using this digital twin allows for further optimization of the system by allowing for experimentation with new data from the cloud without having to halt production or sacrifice safety, as the new processes can be refined virtually until they are ready to be implemented.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] A digital twin can also serve as a training ground for new employees who won't have to worry about real impacts on the live system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] IoT frameworks help support the interaction between "things" and allow for more complex structures like distributed computing and the development of distributed applications.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The term industrial internet of things is often encountered in the manufacturing industries, referring to the industrial subset of the IoT.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Potential benefits of the industrial internet of things include improved productivity, improved reliability, analytics and the transformation of the workplace.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The potential of growth by implementing IIoT is predicted to generate $15 trillion of global GDP by 2030.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] While connectivity and data acquisition are imperative for IIoT, they are not the end goals, but rather the foundation and path to something bigger.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Of all the technologies, predictive maintenance is an "easier” application, as it is applicable to existing assets and management systems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Intelligent maintenance systems can reduce unexpected downtime and increase productivity, which is projected to save up to 12% over scheduled repairs, reduce overall maintenance costs up to 30%, and eliminate breakdowns up to 70%, according to some studies.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Cyber-physical systems (CPS) are the core technology of industrial big data and they will be an interface between human and the cyber world.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Integration of sensing and actuation systems connected to the Internet can optimize energy consumption as a whole.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] It is expected that IoT devices will be integrated into all forms of energy consuming devices (switches, power outlets, bulbs, televisions, etc.) and be able to communicate with the utility supply company in order to effectively balance power generation and energy usage.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) devices connected to the Internet backbone, electric utilities can not only collect data from end-user connections, but also manage other distribution automation devices like transformers and reclosers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Using IIoT in car manufacturing implies the digitalization of all elements of production.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Software, machines, and humans are interconnected, enabling suppliers and manufacturers to rapidly respond to changing standards.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT enables efficient and cost-effective production by moving data from the customers to the company's systems, and then to individual sections of the production process.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIoT, new tools and functionalities can be included in the manufacturing process.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] For example, 3D printers simplify the way of shaping pressing tools by printing the shape directly from steel granulate.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] These tools enable new possibilities for designing (with high precision).
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Customization of vehicles is also enabled by IIoT due to the modularity and connectivity of this technology.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] While in the past they worked separately, IIoT now enables humans and robots to cooperate.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Robots take on heavy and repetitive activities, so the manufacturing cycles are quicker and the vehicle comes to the market more rapidly.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Factories can quickly identify potential maintenance issues before they lead to downtime and many of them are moving to a 24-hour production plant, due to higher security and efficiency.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The majority of automotive manufacturers companies have production plants in different countries, where different components of the same vehicle are built.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT makes it possible to connect these production plants to each other, creating the possibility to move within facilities.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Big data can be visually monitored which enables companies to respond faster to fluctuations in production and demand.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT support, large amounts of raw data can be stored and sent by the drilling gear and research stations for cloud storage and analysis.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT technologies, the oil and gas industry has the capability to connect machines, devices, sensors, and people through interconnectivity, which can help companies better address fluctuations in demand and pricing, address cybersecurity, and minimize environmental impact.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Across the supply chain, IIOT can improve the maintenance process, the overall safety, and connectivity.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Drones can be used to detect possible oil and gas leaks at an early stage and at locations that are difficult to reach (e.g. offshore).
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] They can also be used to identify weak spots in complex networks of pipelines with built-in thermal imaging systems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Increased connectivity (data integration and communication) can help companies with adjusting the production levels based on real-time data of inventory, storage, distribution pace, and forecasted demand.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows monitoring of pipeline threats, improving risk management, and providing situational awareness.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Benefits also apply to specific processes of the oil and gas industry.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The exploration process of oil and gas can be done more precisely with 4D models built by seismic imaging.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] These models map fluctuations in oil reserves and gas levels, they strive to point out the exact quantity of resources needed, and they forecast the lifespan of wells.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The application of smart sensors and automated drillers gives companies the opportunity to monitor and produce more efficiently.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Further, the storing process can also be improved with the implementation of IIOT by collecting and analyzing real-time data to monitor inventory levels and temperature control.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] IIOT can enhance the transportation process of oil and gas by implementing smart sensors and thermal detectors to give real-time geolocation data and monitor the products for safety reasons.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] These smart sensors can monitor the refinery processes, and enhance safety.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The demand for products can be forecasted more precisely and automatically be communicated to the refineries and production plants to adjust production levels.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] In the agriculture industry, IIoT helps farmers to make decisions about when to harvest.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Sensors collect data about soil and weather conditions and propose schedules for fertilizing and irrigating.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Some livestock farms implant microchips into animals.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows the farmers not only to trace their animals, but also pull up information about the lineage, weight, or health.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The integration of IIoT data in the photovoltaic (PV) industry can significantly enhance the efficiency, reliability, and performance of solar power systems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT with AI data can be utilized for real-time monitoring, performance optimization, fault detection, diagnostics.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] As the IIoT expands, new security concerns arise with it.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Every new device or component that connects to the IIoT can become a potential liability.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Gartner estimates that by 2020, more than 25% of recognized attacks on enterprises will involve IoT-connected systems, despite accounting for less than 10% of IT security budgets.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Existing cybersecurity measures are vastly inferior for Internet-connected devices compared to their traditional computer counterparts, which can allow for them to be hijacked for DDoS-based attacks by botnets like Mirai.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Another possibility is the infection of Internet-connected industrial controllers, like in the case of Stuxnet, without the need for physical access to the system to spread the worm.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Additionally, IIoT-enabled devices can allow for more “traditional” forms of cybercrime, as in the case of the 2013 Target data breach, where information was stolen after hackers gained access to Target's networks via credentials stolen from a third party HVAC vendor.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] The pharmaceutical manufacturing industry has been slow to adopt IIoT advances because of security concerns such as these.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the difficulties in providing security solutions in IIoT applications is the fragmented nature of the hardware.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Consequently, security architectures are turning towards designs that are software-based or device-agnostic.
[src:opc-ua-deep/industrial-internet-of-things] Hardware-based approaches, like the use of data diodes, are often used when connecting critical infrastructure.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] An **information model** in software engineering is a representation of concepts and the relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Typically it specifies relations between kinds of things, but may also include relations with individual things.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements or knowledge for the domain context.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The term *information model* in general is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In those cases, the concept is specialised to facility information model, building information model, plant information model, etc.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Within the field of software engineering and data modeling, an information model is usually an abstract, formal representation of entity types that may include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or occurrences, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In 1976, an entity-relationship (ER) graphic notation was introduced by Peter Chen.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] He stressed that it was a "semantic" modelling technique and independent of any database modelling techniques such as Hierarchical, CODASYL, Relational etc.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Since then, languages for information models have continued to evolve.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Some examples are the Integrated Definition Language 1 Extended (IDEF1X), the EXPRESS language and the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Research by contemporaries of Peter Chen such as J.R.Abrial (1974) and G.M Nijssen (1976) led to today's Fact Oriented Modeling (FOM) languages which are based on linguistic propositions rather than on "entities".
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] FOM tools can be used to generate an ER model which means that the modeler can avoid the time-consuming and error prone practice of manual normalization.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Object-Role Modeling language (ORM) and Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling (FCO-IM) are both research results developed in the early 1990s, based upon earlier research.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In the 1980s there were several approaches to extend Chen’s Entity Relationship Model.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Also important in this decade is REMORA by Colette Rolland.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The ICAM Definition (IDEF) Language was developed from the U.S.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Air Force ICAM Program during the 1976 to 1982 timeframe.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The objective of the ICAM Program, according to Lee (1999), was to increase manufacturing productivity through the systematic application of computer technology.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] IDEF includes three different modeling methods: IDEF0, IDEF1, and IDEF2 for producing a functional model, an information model, and a dynamic model respectively.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It is a graphical representation and is designed using the ER approach and the relational theory.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It is used to represent the “real world” in terms of entities, attributes, and relationships between entities.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Normalization is enforced by KEY Structures and KEY Migration.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The language identifies property groupings (Aggregation) to form complete entity definitions.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] EXPRESS was created as ISO 10303-11 for formally specifying information requirements of product data model.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It is part of a suite of standards informally known as the STandard for the Exchange of Product model data (STEP).
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It was first introduced in the early 1990s.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The language, according to Lee (1999), is a textual representation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In addition, a graphical subset of EXPRESS called EXPRESS-G is available.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] EXPRESS is based on programming languages and the O-O paradigm.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] A number of languages have contributed to EXPRESS.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In particular, Ada, Algol, C, C++, Euler, Modula-2, Pascal, PL/1, and SQL.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] EXPRESS consists of language elements that allow an unambiguous object definition and specification of constraints on the objects defined.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It uses SCHEMA declaration to provide partitioning and it supports specification of data properties, constraints, and operations.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a modeling language for specifying, visualizing, constructing, and documenting the artifacts, rather than processes, of software systems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] It was conceived originally by Grady Booch, James Rumbaugh, and Ivar Jacobson.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] UML was approved by the Object Management Group (OMG) as a standard in 1997.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The language, according to Lee (1999), is non-proprietary and is available to the public.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The language is based on the objected-oriented paradigm.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] UML contains notations and rules and is designed to represent data requirements in terms of O-O diagrams.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] UML organizes a model in a number of views that present different aspects of a system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The contents of a view are described in diagrams that are graphs with model elements.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] A diagram contains model elements that represent common O-O concepts such as classes, objects, messages, and relationships among these concepts.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] IDEF1X, EXPRESS, and UML all can be used to create a conceptual model and, according to Lee (1999), each has its own characteristics.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Although some may lead to a natural usage (e.g., implementation), one is not necessarily better than another.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In practice, it may require more than one language to develop all information models when an application is complex.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] In fact, the modeling practice is often more important than the language chosen.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Information models can also be expressed in formalized natural languages, such as Gellish.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Gellish, which has natural language variants Gellish Formal English, Gellish Formal Dutch (Gellish Formeel Nederlands), etc. is an information representation language or modeling language that is defined in the Gellish smart Dictionary-Taxonomy, which has the form of a Taxonomy/Ontology.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] A Gellish Database is not only suitable to store information models, but also knowledge models, requirements models and dictionaries, taxonomies and ontologies.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Information models in Gellish English use Gellish Formal English expressions.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Such Gellish expressions use names of concepts (such as 'city') and relation types (such as ⟨is located in⟩ and ⟨is classified as a⟩) that should be selected from the Gellish Formal English Dictionary-Taxonomy (or of your own domain dictionary).
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The Gellish English Dictionary-Taxonomy enables the creation of semantically rich information models, because the dictionary contains definitions of more than 40000 concepts, including more than 600 standard relation types.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Thus, an information model in Gellish consists of a collection of Gellish expressions that use those phrases and dictionary concepts to express facts or make statements, queries and answers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The Distributed Management Task Force (DMTF) provides a standard set of information models for various enterprise domains under the general title of the Common Information Model (CIM).
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] Specific information models are derived from CIM for particular management domains.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The TeleManagement Forum (TMF) has defined an advanced model for the Telecommunication domain (the Shared Information/Data model, or SID) as another.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] This includes views from the business, service and resource domains within the Telecommunication industry.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The TMF has established a set of principles that an OSS integration should adopt, along with a set of models that provide standardized approaches.
[src:opc-ua-deep/information-model] The models interact with the information model (the Shared Information/Data Model, or SID), via a process model (the Business Process Framework (eTOM), or eTOM) and a life cycle model.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Although developed by the same organization, OPC UA differs significantly from its predecessor, Open Platform Communications (OPC).
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The Foundation's goal for OPC UA was to provide a path forward from the original OPC communications model (namely the Microsoft Windows-only process exchange COM/DCOM) that would better meet the emerging needs of industrial automation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] After more than three years of specification work and another year for a prototype implementation, the first version of the Unified Architecture was released in 2006.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The current version of the specification is on 1.04 (22 November 2017).
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The new version of OPC UA now has added publish/subscribe in addition to the client/server communications infrastructure.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] These drawbacks along with a number of other considerations pushed the decision to develop a new and independent stack for OPC UA, which replaces COM/DCOM.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This communication stack reflects the beginning of various innovations.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC UA architecture is a service-oriented architecture (SOA) and is based on different logical levels.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] OPC Base Services are abstract method descriptions, which are protocol independent and provide the basis for OPC UA functionality.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The transport layer puts these methods into a protocol, which means it serializes/deserializes the data and transmits it over the network.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Two protocols are specified for this purpose.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] One is a binary TCP protocol, optimized for high performance and the second is Web service-oriented.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC information model is a Mesh Network based on nodes.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] These nodes can include any kind of meta information, and are similar to the objects of object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] A node can have attributes for read access such as DataAccess (DA), HistoricDataAccess (HDA), methods that can be called (Commands), and triggered events that can be transmitted (such as AlarmEvent (AE), DataAccess, and DataChange).
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Nodes hold process data as well as other types of metadata.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC namespace contains the type-model.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The namespace is a URI that identifies the naming authority responsible for assigning the identifier element of the NodeId.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Naming authorities include the local Server, the underlying system, standards bodies and consortia.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] It is expected that most Nodes will use the URI of the Server or of the underlying system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Client software can verify what profiles a server supports.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This is necessary to obtain information, if a server only supports DA functionality or additionally AE, HDA, etc.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Additionally, information can be obtained about whether a server supports a given profile.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] At the OPC UA DevCon in October 2006, in Munich the first prototypes were presented live.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Various UA Servers have been shown on a Beckhoff programmable logic controller and an embedded test board from Euros.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The Beckhoff PLC is based on Windows XP Embedded and the embedded controller is based on the real-time operating system Euros.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The company Embedded Labs Ltd demonstrated an OPC UA Server based on their own C++ UA Stack executing on a single chip ARM microcontroller with 64kB RAM.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] In October 2012 the German Fraunhofer-Application Center IOSB-INA and the Institute for industrial Information Technologies (inIT) showed that an OPC UA server is scalable down to 15 kB RAM and 10 kB ROM and therefore usable at chip level.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The current version of the specification is 1.05.06, and was released on 22 October, 2025.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Additionally, part 100 Devices, and part 200 Industrial Automation are also available.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] These build on the core set of specifications, and adds new common definitions that then are used in different companion specifications.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] E.g. both *OPC UA for Analyser Devices* and *OPC UA for Machinery* builds directly on part 100.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] In contrast to the COM-based specifications, the UA specifications are not pure application specifications.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] They describe typical UA internal mechanisms, which get handled through the communication stack and are normally only of interest for those that port a stack to a specific target or those that want to implement their own UA stack.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC UA application developers code against the OPC UA API and therefore mainly use API documentation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Nevertheless, part 3, 4, and 5 may be of interest for application developers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] OPC UA is a versatile industrial communication protocol that is designed to be transport-agnostic, and operate over several transport mechanisms, each corresponding to different layers of the OSI model.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] It can use, TCP, UDP or Ethernet directly, or it can also be encapsulated within higher-level application protocols such as HTTPS, WebSockets, AMQP, and MQTT.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The architecture of a UA application, independent of whether it is the server or client part, is structured into levels.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Some parts equalize to the former COM Proxy/Stubs and get provided by the OPC Foundation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The portability level is new; it simplifies porting the UA ANSI C stack to other target platforms.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] A port layer for Windows and Linux is also provided by the OPC Foundation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] UA Security consists of authentication and authorization, encryption and data integrity via signatures.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] For Web Services the WS-SecureConversation gets used and is therefore compatible with .NET and other SO–AP implementations.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] For the binary variant, the algorithms of WS-SecureConversation have been followed and also converted to a binary equivalent.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This is named as UA Secure Conversation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] There is also a mixed version where the code is binary, but the transport layer is SOAP.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This is a compromise between efficient binary coding and firewall-friendly transmission.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Binary coding always requires UA Secure Conversation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The authentication uses X.509 certificates exclusively.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] It relies on the application developer to choose which certificate store the UA application gets bound to.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] For instance, it is possible to use the public key infrastructure (PKI) of an Active Directory.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] UA APIs are available in several programming languages.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Commercial SDKs are available for C, C++, Java, and .NET.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Open-source stacks are available at least for C, C++, Java, JavaScript(node), Tcl and Python.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The .NET implementation uses ANSI C for the lower levels and implements the rest natively in .NET.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] That means only the handling of the socket and the Message-Chunking gets integrated from the ANSI C stack.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] De-serialization takes place directly in .NET and therefore gets converted directly into .NET structures and objects.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This provides better performance than de-serializing into a C structure first and then copying the data to a .NET structure afterwards.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Various stacks for Java were being developed.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Code directly on the network layer (similar to the current .Net implementation) and de-serialize in Java.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This saves one data copy execution, but still depends on the C stack.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] This was observed to be the most portable, but estimated to take the most engineering effort to implement.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] The Eclipse Milo project provides a pure-Java, open-source, implementation of the UA 1.05 client and server specification.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Apache PLC4X project provides pure-Java, open-source implementation of UA client as well as network level frame descriptions which can be used for cross-language implementations.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] Alternatively, there is the simple variant to only support the WebService protocol.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] For that, a SOAP Toolkit that supports WS-Security is needed.
[src:opc-ua-deep/opc-unified-architecture] IEC 62541 is a standard for OPC Unified Architecture.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] After the initial release in 1996, the OPC Foundation was created to maintain the standards.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Since OPC has been adopted beyond the field of process control, the OPC Foundation changed its name to Open Platform Communications in 2011.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The name change reflects the applications of OPC technology for applications in building automation, discrete manufacturing, process control and others.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC has also grown beyond its original OLE implementation to include other data transportation technologies including Microsoft Corporation's .NET Framework, XML, and even the OPC Foundation's binary-encoded TCP format.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The OPC specification was based on the OLE, COM, and DCOM technologies developed by Microsoft Corporation for the Microsoft Windows operating system family.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The specification defined a standard set of objects, interfaces e.g.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] IDL and methods for use in process control and manufacturing automation applications to facilitate interoperability.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The most common OPC specification is OPC Data Access, which is used for reading and writing real-time data.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] When vendors refer to "OPC" generically, they typically mean OPC Data Access (OPC DA).
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC DA itself has gone through three major revisions since its inception.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Versions are backwards compatible, in that a version 3 OPC Server can still be accessed by a version 1 OPC Client, since the specifications add functionality, but still require the older version to be implemented as well.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] However, a client could be written that does not support the older functions since everything can be done using the newer ones, thus a DA-3-compatible client will not necessarily work with a DA 1.0 Server.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] In addition OPC DA specification, the OPC Foundation maintains the OPC Historical Data Access (HDA) specification.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] In contrast to the real time data that is accessible with OPC DA, OPC HDA allows access and retrieval of archived data.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The OPC Alarms and Events specification is maintained by the OPC Foundation, and defines the exchange of alarm and event type message information, as well as variable states and state management.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] By 2002, the specification was compared to Fieldbus and other previous standards.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] An OPC Express Interface, known as OPC Xi, was approved in November, 2009, for the .NET Framework.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC Xi used Windows Communication Foundation instead of DCOM, so it can be configured for communication across the enhanced security of network address translation (NAT).
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] About the same time, the OPC Unified Architecture (UA) was developed for platform independence.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] UA can be implemented with Java, Microsoft .NET, or C, eliminating the need to use a Microsoft Windows platform of earlier OPC versions.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] UA combined the functionality of the existing OPC interfaces with new technologies such as XML and Web services to deliver higher level manufacturing execution system (MES) and enterprise resource planning (ERP) support.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The first working group for UA met in 2003, version 1.0 was published in 2006.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] On September 16, 2010, The OPC Foundation and the MTConnect Institute announced cooperation to ensure interoperability and consistency between the two standards.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC was designed to provide a common bridge for Windows-based software applications and process control hardware.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Standards define consistent methods of accessing field data from plant floor devices.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] This method remains the same regardless of the type and source of data.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] An OPC Server for one hardware device provides the same methods for an OPC client to access its data as any other OPC Server for any hardware device.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] The aim was to reduce the amount of duplicated effort required from hardware manufacturers and their software partners, and from the supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and other human-machine interface (HMI) producers in order to interface the two.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Once a hardware manufacturer had developed their OPC Server for the new hardware device, their work was done with regards to allowing any 'top end' to access their device, and once the SCADA producer had developed their OPC client, it allowed access to any hardware with an OPC compliant server.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC servers provide a method for different software packages (as long as it is an OPC client) to access data from a process control device, such as a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS).
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Traditionally, any time a package needed access to data from a device, a custom interface or driver had to be written.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] There is nothing in the OPC specifications to restrict the server to providing access to a process control device.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC Servers can be written for anything from getting the internal temperature of a microprocessor to the current temperature in Monument Valley.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Once an OPC Server is written for a particular device, it can be reused by any application that is able to act as an OPC client.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC servers can be linked and communicate to other servers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] OPC servers use Microsoft's OLE technology (also known as the Component Object Model, or COM) to communicate with clients.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] COM technology permits a standard for real-time information exchange between software applications and process hardware to be defined.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] Some OPC specifications are published, but others are available only to members of the OPC Foundation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] So while no company "owns" OPC and anyone can develop an OPC server whether or not they are a member of the OPC Foundation, non-members will not necessarily be using the latest specifications.
[src:opc-ua-deep/open-platform-communications] It is up to each company that requires OPC products to ensure that their products are certified and that their system integrators have the necessary training.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] In software engineering, **service-oriented architecture** (**SOA**) is an architectural style that focuses on discrete services instead of a monolithic design.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is a good choice for system integration.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] By consequence, it is also applied in the field of software design where services are provided to the other components by application components, through a communication protocol over a network.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] A service is a discrete unit of functionality that can be accessed remotely and acted upon and updated independently, such as retrieving a credit card statement online.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is also intended to be independent of vendors, products and technologies.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Service orientation is a way of thinking in terms of services and service-based development and the outcomes of services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] It is a black box for its consumers, meaning the consumer does not have to be aware of the service's inner workings.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Different services can be used in conjunction as a service mesh to provide the functionality of a large software application, a principle SOA shares with modular programming.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture integrates distributed, separately maintained and deployed software components.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] It is enabled by technologies and standards that facilitate components' communication and cooperation over a network, especially over an IP network.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is related to the idea of an API (application programming interface), an interface or communication protocol between different parts of a computer program intended to simplify the implementation and maintenance of software.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] An API can be thought of as the service, and the SOA the architecture that allows the service to operate.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Note that Service-Oriented Architecture must not be confused with Service Based Architecture as those are two different architectural styles.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] In SOA, services use protocols that describe how they pass and parse messages using description metadata.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] This metadata describes both the functional characteristics of the service and quality-of-service characteristics.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture aims to allow users to combine large chunks of functionality to form applications which are built purely from existing services and combining them in an ad hoc manner.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] A service presents a simple interface to the requester that abstracts away the underlying complexity acting as a black box.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Further users can also access these independent services without any knowledge of their internal implementation.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The related buzzword service-orientation promotes *loose coupling* between services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA separates functions into distinct units, or services, which developers make accessible over a network in order to allow users to combine and reuse them in the production of applications.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] These services and their corresponding consumers communicate with each other by passing data in a well-defined, shared format, or by coordinating an activity between two or more services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA can be seen as part of the continuum which ranges from the older concept of distributed computing and modular programming, through SOA, and on to practices of mashups, SaaS, and cloud computing (which some see as the offspring of SOA).
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] There are no industry standards relating to the exact composition of a service-oriented architecture, although many industry sources have published their own principles.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] documents within a given set of services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The relationship between services is minimized to the level that they are only aware of their existence.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be called from anywhere within the network that it is located no matter where it is present.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services should be designed to be long lived.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Where possible, services should avoid forcing consumers to change if they do not require new features; if you call a service today, you should be able to call the same service tomorrow.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The services act as black boxes, that is their inner logic is hidden from the consumers.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services are independent and control the functionality they encapsulate, from a Design-time and a run-time perspective.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services are stateless, that is either return the requested value or give an exception hence minimizing resource use.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] A principle to ensure services have an adequate size and scope.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The functionality provided by the service to the user must be relevant.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services are decomposed or consolidated (normalized) to minimize redundancy.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] These are the cases where performance optimization, access, and aggregation are required.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be used to compose other services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services are supplemented with communicative meta data by which they can be effectively discovered and interpreted.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Logic is divided into various services, to promote reuse of code.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Many services which were not initially planned under SOA, may get encapsulated or become a part of SOA.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] It creates a web service and provides its information to the service registry.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] and what sort of trading partner agreements are required to use the service.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Its main functionality is to make information regarding the web service available to any potential requester.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Whoever implements the broker decides the scope of the broker.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Public brokers are available anywhere and everywhere but private brokers are only available to a limited amount of public.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] It locates entries in the broker registry using various find operations and then binds to the service provider in order to invoke one of its web services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Whichever service the service-consumers need, they have to take it into the brokers, bind it with respective service and then use it.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] They can access multiple services if the service provides multiple services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The service consumer–provider relationship is governed by a standardized service contract, which has a business part, a functional part and a technical part.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Service composition patterns have two broad, high-level architectural styles: choreography and orchestration.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Lower level enterprise integration patterns that are not bound to a particular architectural style continue to be relevant and eligible in SOA design.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture can be implemented with web services or Microservices.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] This is done to make the functional building-blocks accessible over standard Internet protocols that are independent of platforms and programming languages.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] These services can represent either new applications or just wrappers around existing legacy systems to make them network-enabled.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Implementers commonly build SOAs using web services standards.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] One example is SOAP, which has gained broad industry acceptance after the recommendation of Version 1.2 from the W3C (World Wide Web Consortium) in 2003.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] These standards (also referred to as web service specifications) also provide greater interoperability and some protection from lock-in to proprietary vendor software.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] One can, however, also implement SOA using any other service-based technology, such as Jini, CORBA, Internet Communications Engine, REST, or gRPC.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Implementations can use one or more of these protocols and, for example, might use a file-system mechanism to communicate data following a defined interface specification between processes conforming to the SOA concept.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The key is independent services with defined interfaces that can be called to perform their tasks in a standard way, without a service having foreknowledge of the calling application, and without the application having or needing knowledge of how the service actually performs its tasks.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA enables the development of applications that are built by combining loosely coupled and interoperable services.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] These services inter-operate based on a formal definition (or contract, e.g., WSDL) that is independent of the underlying platform and programming language.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] The interface definition hides the implementation of the language-specific service.
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] SOA-based systems can therefore function independently of development technologies and platforms (such as Java, .NET, etc.).
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Services written in C# running on .NET platforms and services written in Java running on Java EE platforms, for example, can both be consumed by a common composite application (or client).
[src:opc-ua-deep/service-oriented-architecture] Applications running on either platform can also consume services running on the other as web services that facilitate reuse.
